     \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H13N3O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-(carbamimidamido)pentanoic acid precursor analog\",\n      \"common_name\": \"citrulline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H13N3O3/c7-4(5(10)11)2-1-3-9-6(8)12/h4H,1-3,7H2,(H,10,11)(H2,8,9,12)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHNO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"cyanic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHNO/c2-1-3/h(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamic acid/glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C12H27N7O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"arginylarginine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Arg-Arg dipeptide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite\", \"mackinawite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic alkaline vent conditions; H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface CO2 hydrogenation on Fe-S phases gives reduced C1 products including formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fe-S catalyzed CO2 reduction in hydrothermal settings is consistent with iron-sulfur world chemistry and vent carbon fixation scenarios, providing reduced carbon feedstocks that can seed surface photochemical networks; arginine itself is not formed hydrothermally. This step is used as environmental input rather than a direct arginine-forming step (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Patel et al., 2015; Miller, 1986).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface generation of formaldehyde from reduced C1 feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated shallow pool; borate stabilizes carbonyl products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical oxidation-state reorganization of reduced C1 species yields formaldehyde in surface pools.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This connection is included to maintain a connected Hydrothermal-to-Surface network supplying carbonyl chemistry to HCN-rich environments. It is more speculative than Patel's arginine-specific sequence but is consistent with surface photochemical carbonyl generation used broadly in prebiotic chemistry; the arginine literature emphasizes the need for connected cyanide-rich surface systems rather than direct hydrothermal arginine synthesis (Patel et al., 2015; Pol et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Photochemical generation/concentration of HCN in cyanosulfidic surface pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV exposure; anoxic, evaporitic concentration cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven surface photochemistry and concentration processes generate and accumulate cyanide-bearing feedstocks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. require HCN-rich cyanosulfidic settings, and the broader prebiotic literature treats HCN as a major feedstock in UV-irradiated surface ponds. This step is a network-supply step, not a direct arginine-forming transformation, but is necessary to connect environmental sources to the validated homologation chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Miller, 1986; Pol et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanamide formation and concentration\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry concentration; UV-active pond chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanide-derived nitrogen chemistry under concentrating surface conditions yields cyanamide as a guanidinylating agent.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanamide is explicitly identified in Patel et al. as the key =NH/guanidino-group donor in the arginine precursor sequence. This network step represents its buildup in surface environments and is required to feed the documented downstream chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Pol et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic coupling of HCN and acetylene to acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox system with H2S; mineral support by sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV around 300 nm; cyanosulfidic photoredox; reported up to ~25% yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven Cu photoredox coupling of cyanide chemistry with acetylene in the presence of H2S affords acrylonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the key documented entry into the arginine-specific pathway: Patel et al. reported acrylonitrile formation from HCN and acetylene under cyanosulfidic photoredox conditions, with H2S as reductant and yields above 25% in the relevant step (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonia addition to acrylonitrile giving beta-aminopropionitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface concentration on clay with cyanosulfidic medium\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous NH3 addition following acrylonitrile formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of ammonia across activated nitrile-containing unsaturation furnishes beta-aminopropionitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Beta-aminopropionitrile is explicitly identified as a central intermediate in the Patel arginine scheme, produced from acrylonitrile plus ammonia. Montmorillonite is included as a plausible concentrating mineral for cationic/basic intermediates in surface settings (Patel et al., 2015; ScienceDirect montmorillonite adsorption study, 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Photoreduction of beta-aminopropionitrile to beta-aminopropionaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photoreduction with H2S reductant\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"acidic photoreduction phase; stepwise reagent addition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV/H2S-mediated reductive conversion of nitrile-bearing precursor into the corresponding aldehyde stage in the homologation cascade.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. describe UV-driven reduction of beta-aminopropionitrile to beta-aminopropionaldehyde prior to cyanamide capture. This step is part of the core literature-supported arginine precursor pathway (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanamide capture to cyclic guanidinium hemiaminal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface concentration on clay; UV-active pool\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"rapid addition of cyanamide to beta-aminopropionaldehyde\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The aldehyde reacts with cyanamide to form a guanidinium-bearing cyclic hemiaminal intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The guanidinium installation problem is central to prebiotic arginine synthesis, and Patel et al. specifically invoke cyanamide addition to the reduced aldehyde to form a cyclic guanidinium hemiaminal. This is one of the most important literature-grounded steps because it introduces the future guanidino functionality (Patel et al., 2015; Pol et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Homologation and thiolactam formation from cyclic guanidinium intermediate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV photoreduction with H2S; cyanosulfidic homologation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"stepwise HCN addition and reduction through alpha-hydroxythioamide stage to thiolactam\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Kiliani-Fischer-type cyanide homologation plus sulfur-mediated photoreduction gives an alpha-hydroxythioamide that cyclizes into gamma-butyrothiolactam.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. describe further HCN addition and photoreduction steps after guanidinium-hemiaminal formation, leading through sulfur-containing intermediates to gamma-butyrothiolactam. This captures the documented middle section of the arginine aminonitrile cascade (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Final cyanosulfidic homologation to arginine aminonitrile precursor\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV/H2S reduction and clay concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"continued stepwise HCN addition and reduction; neutral to slightly basic finishing stage\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further reduction and cyanide incorporation convert the thiolactam-stage intermediate into the compound-46-type alpha-aminonitrile precursor to arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. identify a final alpha-aminonitrile precursor (compound 46 type) that hydrolyzes to arginine. This reaction collapses the final literature-described homologation sequence into a single network node while preserving the documented mechanistic direction (Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of arginine aminonitrile to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrolysis in aqueous prebiotic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis converts the alpha-aminonitrile to the corresponding alpha-amino acid arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. explicitly propose that simple alkaline hydrolysis of the compound-46-type aminonitrile affords arginine. The literature identifies hydrolysis as plausible but also notes that nitrile hydrolysis may be kinetically slow, making this a likely bottleneck in natural accumulation (Patel et al., 2015; Pol et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative hydrothermal glutamate formation by reductive amination network\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite\", \"greigite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe-S mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing, anoxic vent conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe-S-mediated carbon fixation and amination network yields alpha-amino dicarboxylate analogs including glutamate-like products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glutamate is discussed by Glavin et al. as a conceivable prebiotic entry point into metabolism-like Orn/Cit/Arg chemistry, but no direct arginine synthesis from this route has been demonstrated. This hydrothermal step is therefore speculative and included only to connect the literature-mentioned alternative biosynthetic analogy into the network (Glavin et al., 2025; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Pol et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative conversion of glutamate to ornithine analogue\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonia-rich prebiotic pond; metabolism-analog route\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"A not-yet-demonstrated sequence of reduction/transamination/decarboxylation transforms glutamate-like precursor into ornithine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The glutamate to ornithine idea is specifically mentioned as a conceivable metabolism-analog route but has not been experimentally demonstrated under prebiotic conditions. It is included as a literature-anchored speculative branch rather than an established route (Glavin et al., 2025; Pol et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative carbamoylation of ornithine to citrulline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate/clay concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry pond cycles with cyanate or carbamoyl donor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbamoyl transfer from cyanate-like donor to ornithine gives citrulline-like product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies carbamoylation of ornithine by cyanate/urea-like donors as a conceivable but unproven prebiotic step toward arginine. This reaction is explicitly speculative and included to represent the open-question Orn/Cit branch noted in the review (Glavin et al., 2025; Pol et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative guanidinylation of citrulline to arginine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonia-rich pond chemistry; cyanamide-assisted guanidino-group completion\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further amidino/guanidino transfer to citrulline-like intermediate yields arginine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"No direct prebiotic demonstration of citrulline-to-arginine exists in the supplied literature. This step is included only because the Orn/Cit/Arg analogy is mentioned as a possible route if suitable carbamoyl/guanidino chemistry can occur; it should be regarded as highly speculative (Glavin et al., 2025; Pol et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Arginine concentration and peptide coupling to Arg-Arg depsipeptide/dipeptide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces; concentration enhanced by clay adsorption\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Once arginine is present, dehydration/condensation under wet-dry cycles promotes oligomerization into peptide-like products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Frenkel-Pinter and coworkers showed that arginine, when present, readily participates in wet-dry oligomerization/depsipeptide formation. This does not form arginine but demonstrates its biochemical integration and selective concentration relevance after synthesis (Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2019/2020; ScienceDirect montmorillonite adsorption study, 2024).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Core Patel route from supplied HCN pool\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct cyanosulfidic route beginning from available HCN, acetylene, NH3, H2S, and cyanamide in a UV-irradiated surface pond.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal carbon feeding into Patel route\",\n      \"description\": \"Reduced carbon from hydrothermal formate feeds surface carbonyl chemistry, then enters HCN-rich cyanosulfidic arginine synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-first route with pre-existing cyanamide\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN generated in surface pools converges with independently available cyanamide before homologation to arginine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Clay-concentrated beta-aminopropionitrile route\",\n      \"description\": \"Acrylonitrile formed photochemically is trapped and aminated on clay-rich shorelines, then advanced through the Patel sequence.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldehyde-capture branch of the Patel route\",\n      \"description\": \"The reduced aldehyde intermediate is formed first, then guanidinium installation by cyanamide drives onward homologation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Thiolactam-to-arginine branch\",\n      \"description\": \"A later-stage route emphasizing sulfur-assisted thiolactam intermediate conversion into the final aminonitrile precursor and then arginine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-HCN abbreviated route\",\n      \"description\": \"Reduced C1 chemistry supplies formaldehyde and then HCN, but cyanamide is assumed already present from surface concentration cycles.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Parallel HCN and cyanamide convergence route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN and cyanamide are generated in parallel in surface systems and converge at guanidinium-installation chemistry leading to arginine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Speculative glutamate-ornithine-citrulline pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Metabolism-analog branch from hydrothermal glutamate through ornithine and citrulline to arginine; included as literature-noted but unproven.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Arginine utilization after synthesis\",\n      \"description\": \"Once arginine is produced by the Patel route, it is concentrated and incorporated into peptide-like products under wet-dry biochemical cycling.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Arginine", "overall_strategy": "This network centers on the only detailed literature-grounded prebiotic route to arginine: the cyanosulfidic homologation sequence of Patel et al. (2015), embedded within a broader connected network that supplies HCN, NH3, and carbon feedstocks from hydrothermal and surface settings, then finishes by hydrolysis and peptide incorporation in biochemical settings. Because no validated one-step prebiotic synthesis of arginine exists, the network explicitly uses convergent feeding of shared hubs (HCN, NH3, acrylonitrile, beta-aminopropionitrile, and the arginine aminonitrile precursor) into multiple literature-consistent subroutes. Ten distinct pathways are represented as alternative route combinations through the same connected bipartite graph, with speculative links clearly labeled where needed to maintain connectivity and environmental interconnection.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {