ce mediated CO2 reduction under hydrothermal redox gradients gives C1 reduced carbon as formate.", "reasoning": "Included as literature-consistent hydrothermal feedstock provisioning rather than arginine-specific chemistry. Fe-S minerals are established for CO2 reduction in vent scenarios and provide environmental interconnection to surface chemistry; no direct arginine synthesis is claimed here. This follows the hydrothermal context summarized in the report and is consistent with Fe-S mediated prebiotic carbon fixation discussions linked to vent chemistry (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Glavin et al., 2025 review context)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal further reduction to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal setting; reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Sequential mineral-catalyzed reduction and C-C bond-forming carbon fixation yields acetate-like products.", "reasoning": "Used only to maintain a connected hydrothermal carbon-fixation module consistent with the framework requirement; not claimed as an arginine route. Hydrothermal Fe-S/carbon fixation chemistry is discussed in the supplied report as general provisioning chemistry, distinct from the actual arginine-forming cyanide sequence (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Glavin et al., 2025)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate generation", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent setting; reductive carbon fixation analog"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-mediated reductive carbon fixation extends C1/C2 pools to alpha-keto acid chemistry, giving pyruvate as a metabolic hub.", "reasoning": "This step is network-scaffolding to satisfy Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical connectivity and the requested hub topology, not a literature-demonstrated entry to arginine. The report specifically notes alpha-keto acid chemistry and Fe-S reductive amination as plausible hydrothermal reactions while acknowledging no demonstrated arginine formation (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Miller, 1986; Pol et al., 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS/FeS2 mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "acidic to mildly reducing hydrothermal conditions; excess NH3"}, "mechanism": "Fe-S catalyzed reductive amination of an alpha-keto acid produces the corresponding amino acid.", "reasoning": "This is directly aligned with the report's citation that FeS/NiS-mediated reductive amination can produce alpha-amino acids from keto acids, while explicitly not extending that evidence to arginine because no guanidino-group installation is demonstrated (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Miller, 1986; Pol et al., 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface cyanosulfidic photoredox formation of acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox with Zn2+ in aqueous UV-irradiated sulfide-rich pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV around 300 nm; H2S reductant; stepwise reagent addition; evaporitic or photic surface pond"}, "mechanism": "HCN and acetylene undergo Cu photoredox-mediated coupling in the presence of sulfide reductant to give acrylonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the key experimentally grounded entry to the arginine route: Patel et al. reported acrylonitrile formation from HCN and acetylene under UV-driven cyanosulfidic conditions, with yields above 25%. The mineral field here reflects the required surface mineral specification while the actual catalytic system follows the literature Cu/Zn/H2S photoredox chemistry (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface ammonia addition to acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface concentration on clay; aqueous NH3", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral to slightly basic aqueous conditions; post-photoredox step"}, "mechanism": "Conjugate addition of ammonia to activated unsaturated nitrile yields beta-aminopropionitrile.", "reasoning": "The report identifies beta-aminopropionitrile from acrylonitrile plus ammonia as a central documented intermediate in the Patel sequence. Montmorillonite is included as a plausible concentrating mineral, while the chemical step itself follows the Patel pathway (Patel et al., 2015; Glavin et al., 2025 review summary)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface cyanamide capture and photoreductive conversion to cyclic guanidinium hemiaminal", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoreduction with H2S; Cu/Zn cyanosulfidic system", "aqueous": "true", "other": "acidic photoreduction segment after cyanamide addition; stepwise reagent delivery"}, "mechanism": "Beta-aminopropionitrile is photoreduced to the corresponding aldehyde, which rapidly adds cyanamide to produce a cyclic guanidinium hemiaminal intermediate.", "reasoning": "This step follows the explicit mechanistic description in the report: beta-aminopropionitrile is reduced to beta-aminopropionaldehyde and then intercepted by cyanamide to form a cyclic guanidinium hemiaminal. This is one of the crucial guanidino-installation steps and directly addresses the literature-identified challenge of guanidinium formation (Patel et al., 2015; Pol et al., 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface HCN homologation and thiolactam formation", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_001", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV/H2S photoreduction in Cu/Zn-enabled cyanosulfidic chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Kiliani-Fischer-type homologation sequence; alpha-hydroxythioamide formation followed by cyclization"}, "mechanism": "HCN addition extends the carbon skeleton, photoreduction gives sulfur-containing intermediates, and intramolecular cyclization produces the guanidino thiolactam.", "reasoning": "The report specifically describes subsequent HCN addition and photoreductive steps leading to an alpha-hydroxythioamide that cyclizes into gamma-butyrothiolactam. This is a core Patel intermediate sequence and should not be replaced by alternative chemistry (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface final homologation to arginine alpha-aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "continued UV/H2S photoreduction with cyanosulfidic reagent pulses", "aqueous": "true", "other": "stepwise HCN addition and reduction; neutral to mildly basic capture s