 supported by the supplied report, which notes that arginine binds montmorillonite much more strongly than neutral amino acids. It provides a realistic post-synthesis concentration mechanism once arginine exists (ScienceDirect study on montmorillonite adsorption, 2024; cited in the report as [11])."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Biochemical wet-dry peptide coupling of alanine and arginine", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null", "null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "false", "other": "wet-dry cycling in hydroxy-acid-rich prebiotic pools; dehydration-condensation context"}, "mechanism": "Concentrated amino acids participate in dehydration-driven condensation/depsipeptide-assisted coupling to give short peptides.", "reasoning": "Frenkel-Pinter and co-workers showed that when arginine is present with hydroxy acids and related monomers, it readily enters oligomeric products under wet-dry cycling. This reaction is included as downstream biochemical relevance after arginine formation rather than as part of arginine synthesis itself (Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2019-2020; cited in the report as [7])."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical Patel cyanosulfidic arginine route", "description": "Direct literature-supported sequence from HCN and acetylene through acrylonitrile, beta-aminopropionitrile, guanidinium intermediates, thiolactam, aminonitrile, and hydrolysis to arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal ammonia provisioning into Patel route", "description": "Hydrothermal generation/availability of ammonia feeds the surface cyanosulfidic route beginning with acrylonitrile amination and ending in arginine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_006",